Sometimes there was music also before the beginning of the play (before the prologue) and between the acts. The music for the plays of Plautus and Terence seems to have been oomposed entirely by slaves. The music was given by a single fluteplayer (tibicen), probably by the oomposer himself, with a double flute, or, perhaps we might say, clarinet, as the instrument bore a greater resemblance to it than to our flute. It was played by blowing into both tubes at the same time. From the didascalice we learn of four different kinds of these instrumenta: tibiae paves, in which the two pipes were of equal length, tibiae impares, in which they were of unoqual length; tibiae sevrcnoe, of which but little is known, though they were probably of equal length32 and duce dextrae tibiae, in which the two tubes were of equal length and identical in key and note. ’

Regarding the lastmentioned tibiae, we are told by Varro that the right tube was for leading (tibio ivrceotioo), the left for aocompanying (tibio surrentino).
